# UT / test-evidence documentation (before -> after walkthrough)

A UT (user/unit test) evidence doc PROVES each acceptance criterion (AC) works by running the real process end-to-end and screenshotting the state before and after. It is evidence, not prose — favour screenshots over explanation.

Stack-agnostic. "The process under test" = whatever transforms the data: a batch / scheduled job, a queue or cron worker, an ETL pipeline, an API endpoint, a UI flow. "Record" = the entity it consumes or produces. Companion operational skill: [`.claude/skills/ut-evidence-doc/SKILL.md`](../../.claude/skills/ut-evidence-doc/SKILL.md).

## When to apply

Asked to create a "UT doc", "UAT doc", "test evidence", "QA walkthrough", or "screenshot proof that each AC works".

## Document shape (minimal, screenshot-heavy)

- One `#` title + ONE intro line (environment + how records were staged). NO "Purpose", "Components", "How to reproduce", or "Results summary" sections.
- One `##` per scenario: `AC1`, `AC2`, ... Each scenario = ONE sentence (the condition + expected outcome) + the before screenshots + the after screenshots, each with a short caption.
- Per scenario, capture:
  - BEFORE: the input record the process will pick up, and the single detail that decides the outcome (the in-scope field for a happy path, or the missing/invalid data for a negative case).
  - AFTER: the record the process created, the output it produced (or the logged error for a negative case), and that record appearing in the downstream report/list.
- Store at `docs/ut/<work-id>/<slug>.md` with a sibling `assets/` folder. Name screenshots predictably: `ac1-before-<what>.png`, `ac1-after-<what>.png`.
- Optionally export a PDF beside the markdown.

## Staging + run protocol

1. For each scenario, FIND a real record the process will pick up. If none qualifies, MODIFY one so it does (e.g. set the due/eligibility field). Prefer real records over synthetic test data.
2. For negative scenarios with no natural record, FORCE the gap on a real record (deactivate/blank the required data).
3. SNAPSHOT everything you modify (persist the original values to a snapshot record/file) so it can be restored.
4. Confirm eligibility and blast radius with a query BEFORE running — only your intended records should get processed.
5. Capture ALL before screenshots, run the process ONCE, then capture ALL after screenshots.
6. VERIFY outcomes with queries (counts, IDs, error codes) before relying on any screenshot.
7. ROLL BACK staged/forced changes from the snapshot; LEAVE the process-created records (the evidence) in place.

## Screenshot capture (tool-agnostic)

- Open the app with an auto-login/session URL, go to each record, take a full-page screenshot, save it with the predictable name, and copy it into the repo `assets/` folder.
- Virtualized or iframed lists (reports, infinite-scroll grids) often can't be searched/sorted via automation. Instead scroll the list's scroll container programmatically until the target row renders, then screenshot. Newest-first sorts usually surface a just-created record at the top of its group.

## Commit (two-commit, explicit staging)

1. Commit 1 — artifacts: the staging/rollback scripts + the UT doc + screenshots + PDF. Stage each path explicitly; never blanket-add a directory.
2. Commit 2 — backfill: update the living/feature doc to link the UT doc + PDF and reference commit 1's short hash.

Only commit when the user asks.

## Anti-patterns

- Adding "Purpose / Components / Reproduce / Summary" sections — keep it to AC header + one line + screenshots.
- Synthetic dummy data when a real eligible record exists.
- Modifying real records without a snapshot + rollback.
- Calling the underlying function directly instead of running the actual process the user ships.
- A screenshot of a 1000-row report that does not actually show the target row — surface it first.
- "See attached screenshot" as the AC description — state the condition + expected outcome in words too.

## Adapting to other projects

This rule names no project, org, language, or framework. Map the generic terms to your stack: "process under test" -> your batch/job/endpoint; "record" -> your entity/row/document; "report/list" -> your downstream view; "query" -> your DB/API read; "auto-login URL" -> your app's session link. Keep `docs/ut/` at the repo root or adjust the path consistently in this rule and the companion skill.
